These days, alternative medicine and treatments have become increasingly popular, and people have mixed views about them. Personally, I believe this is a largely positive development while also recognizing the health risks that come with these alternatives.

Alternative medicine and treatments often provide inexpensive and accessible solutions to people with a specific need that's hard to be addressed otherwise. Cupping, for example, effectively enhances the blood circulation and relaxes fascias in a way that mainstream medicine cannot. That's why it's adopted worldwide -- I still remember with amusement the red circles on the back of Michael Phelps when he appeared in the Olympic Games. On another note, alternatives like palliative care shed a different light on how to approach certain health issues: some patients do not necessarily want to "cure" the disease given the cost and prognosis; instead they may choose to simply live in peace with it.

Of course, it is crucial to be aware of the health risks involved with any treatment. Alternative medicines are especially susceptible to these risks because they often have a long history going back thousands of years in some cases when medical science was unheard of. Cow's urine is a case in point. In India it's used as a traditional tonic for a wide range of applications, but its efficacy is quite dubious outside that culture. A much more unfortunate example is the untimely death of Steve Jobs: reports say he had been treating his cancer on his own, using some method involving meditation and what not, rejecting standard medical advice. Therefore, beware of snake oil.

In conclusion, the popularity of alternative medicine as a complementary to mainstream treatments is a boon to people who need them, provided the associated risks be carefully examined.